**Method 1: Iterative code**

Read lots of java version without finding `O(1)` space solution. Some of them use `substring()`, which could cost `O(n / 2)` each, and some use recursion in addition, which cost more space due to recursion stack.

Here is real space `O(1)` solution, idea is similar to the top voted:
1. Try to match the `substring(out[0], in[0])` and `substring(in[1], out[1])`; 
2. If succeed, increase the `counter` by `2`, then continue to operate on the remaining parts; otherwise, expand by `1` the size of both substrings;
3. Repeat 2 till the 2 substrings meet.

```
    public int longestDecomposition(String text) {
        int out[] = { 0, text.length() }, in[] = out.clone(), counter = 0;
        label:
        while (++in[0] <= --in[1]) {
            for (int i = out[0], j = in[1]; i < in[0]; ++i, ++j)
                if (text.charAt(i) != text.charAt(j))
                    continue label;
            counter += 2;
            out = in.clone();
        }
        return counter + (out[1] > out[0] ? 1 : 0);
    }
```
**Analysis:**

Time: O(n ^ 2), space: O(1).

----
**Method 2: Recursive code**:

```
    public int longestDecomposition(String text) {
        return longestDecomposition(text, 0, text.length());
    }
    private int longestDecomposition(String text, int lo, int hi) {
        label:
        for (int len = 1; len <= (hi - lo) / 2; ++len) {
            for (int i = lo, j = hi - len; i < lo + len; ++i, ++j)
                if (text.charAt(i) != text.charAt(j))
                        continue label;
            return 2 + longestDecomposition(text, lo + len, hi - len);
        }
        return hi - lo < 2 ? hi - lo : 1;
    }
```
**Analysis:**

Time: O(n ^ 2), space: O(n).

