solutions.content:
The main info you need to follow this algorithm is:

* We're comparing chunks, starting at the outer extremes of the text, traveling inward.
* Index `l` points at the first character of the current chunk.
* Index `r` points at one past the last character of the current chunk.
* Index `N-r` points at the first character of the equivalent chunk on the other side of the text.
* We want every match to be as small as possible. As soon as we match, we advance `l`.
* At the end we still need to check whether there's a lone chunk left in the middle.

```C++
int longestDecomposition(const string& text) {
  const int N = text.size();
  const auto tb = text.begin();
  int count = 0, l = 0;
  for (int r = 1; 2*r <= N; ++r)
    if (equal(tb+l, tb+r, tb+N-r))
      count += 2, l = r;
  return count + (2 * l < N);
}
```

