```
class Solution {
public:
    //Return the largest possible number of chunk that forms palindromic relationship inside the given text
    int longestDecomposition(string text) {
        if(text.empty()){ //if the given string is empty, it cannot even have a single chunk.
            return 0;
        }
        vector<int> pTable(text.length());//prefix pattern table essentially used in KMP algorithm
        //1. No segfault: since we have checked empty string case at the beginig
        //2. should be 0, because we are comparing the same character("same" as literally same, not about their value)
        pTable[0] = 0;

        int j = 0;//j pointer pointing the next prefix candidate
        int i = 1;//iterating through the text string to fill up the ptable
        while(i < text.length()){
            if(text[i] == text[j]){//if their character matches
                pTable[i] = j + 1; //record the length of recurring prefix the string(0, i) can have
                ++j;
                ++i;
            }
            else if(j == 0){
                /*to prevent the infinite loop:
                if the two characters are different and there are no more previous characters to be comoapred
                then just move onto the next char in the text to fill up the table
                */
                ++i;
            }
            else{
                //if not match, but still there can be another possible match to previous pattern
                //ex) abacabab == the last abab does not match with abac but the last two character ab matches with the first ab 
                j = pTable[j-1];
            }
        }
        int len = pTable[pTable.size() - 1]; //the length of the last chunk that also occuring at the beginning
        if(len == 0){//if there is no such chunk, then we cannot form a palindrome with multiple chunks
            //Therefore, the smallest palindromic chunk is the string itself.
            return 1;
        }
        else if(len > text.length() / 2){ //Since the chunk is greater than the (text length / 2), so we know that that pattern is continuous
            //In other words, the entire string is made of many of one chunk.
            int chunkLen = text.length() - len;//calculating the shortest chucnk length because we have to maximize the number of chunks
            return text.length() / chunkLen;
        }
        else{
            //(chunkA)(ChunkB)(chunkA) case
            //treat each chunk as another "text" string and get the largest k value of that text thru recurisve call.
            string midStr = text.substr(len, text.length() - (2*len));
            string outerStr = text.substr(0, len);
            return longestDecomposition(midStr) + (2 * longestDecomposition(outerStr));
        }
    }
};
```
Point:
Core: Use Prefix Pattern Table to deductively figure out the length of each side chunk.
3 cases:
1. If the length of each side chunk is 0 --> the only possible chunk is the string itself, so return 1
2. If the length of each side chunk is > (text string length / 2) --> the whole string is made of many of "one type of chunk" --> so find the shortest possible chunk length and return (text string length / the shortest possible chunk length)
3. If the length of each side chuck is <= (text string length / 2) --> (chunkA)(chunkB)(chunkA) case. *Note: chunkB can be an empty string
--> treat each chunk as another "text" and get their larget possible number of chunks through recursive call.

